{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_flagg_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583814/1908041601/0682.xml":{"full_text":"pi\nf\nI But few days to complete your Easter\nshopping. In Footwear you will find our\nstyles most pleasing and attractive.\nLadies\u2019 Buckle Strap and Tie Pumps in\nall sizes, widths and leathers\n$2.00, $2.50, $3.00, $3.50, $4.50\nFor Men\u2014Tan, Patents and all other de\nsirable leathers.\u2018..$3 to $6.50\nBoys and Girls\u2014All kinds of Pumps,\nTies and Sandals.75c to $3\nD. A. RICH, 1913 FIRST AVL\nI OUR HOSIERY SAVES YOU MONEY\nI LOODY WARFARE\nWITH BAD INDIANS\n0\nREPORTS FROM CENTRAL AMER\nICA STATE THAT 60 PERSONS\nHAVE BEEN KILLED IN RECENT\nFIGHTING.\nNew Orleans, April IB.\u2014A report that\nabout 60 whites and Indians have been\nkilled in Nicaragua, in a bloody bush\nwarfare waged by Mosquito Indians, was\nbrought here today by W. R. Coffman of\nBloomington, 111., who was a passenger\non the steamer Dictator from Central\nX i American ports. The death list of whites\nif? I numbers about 20.\nThe fighting started over a month ago\non the Carrlbean coast, where the In\ndians live. Late in February about 100\nIndians attacked Prinapolca Ber, a small\ntown. They hid behind bushes, trees and\nother shelter, pouring into the village\na fire which killed two men. A long,\nhard fight resulted, soldiers and citizen\nvolunteers driving the attackers back\nfrom tree to tree, until about a dozen\nof the Indians iffy dead or mortally\nwounded. The other Indians fled, but\nmany of them were captured and, after\nbeing severely beaten with rawhides, ball\nand chains were placed about their legs\nand they were imprisoneu in improved\nstockades In the woods.\nAnother engagement took place at Cape\nGracias, near the border of Nicaragua\nand Spanish Honduras. Here the casual\nties among the troops were five, but the\nMosquitoes were no more successful than\nbefore and fled to retreats in the moun\ntains. Since then, Mr. Coffman said,\nmany troops have been sent into the Mos\nquito district, and several skirmishes\nhave occurred. It is reported that treach\nery and cunning have been used on both\nsides. Wherever a party of white men\nget a chance they general!y-kill the In\ndians without mercy and the Indians\nhave slain several soldiers whom they\ncaught alone in the forests.\nLAND FRAUD CASES.\nTestimony Is Given Regarding Trans\nfer of Lands.\nWashington, April 15.\u2014In the Hyde-Ben\nson-Dimond-Schneider alleged land fraud\ntrial today, George W. Davis, who was\nformerly a notary in Salem, Ore., and\nwho operated a stone quarry in that stale,\ntestified that he secured applications for\nan assignment of Oregon schol lands\nfrom employes in his quarry at the re\nquest of E. P. McCornach, president of\na Salem bank. Davis said that he paid\nfrom $1 to $2.50 for each assignment. Dis\ntrict Attorney Baker informed the court\nthat the government would connect Davis'\ntestimony with the operations of Hyde.\nT. T. ASHFORD, Freni dent. WM, E. MEADE, Secretary P'\nI Birmingham Paint Glass Co. I\nI Sash, Doors, Blinds, Mantels I\nrtfc. Sole Agents for\nM Hammar\u2019s Prepared Paints.\nMagnite, Cold Water Paint. gf\nlij Rogers\u2019 Stainfloor Finish. g\njt Pratt Lambert Varnishes.\n|^^201^n^01^Thir^Ave^^^Birmingham^la^^^j\n\u2014\u20141.\nBeverage VA/Hislcies\nFor Gentlemen\n1.1 21 Years Guarantee Behind Our Proposition. i\nThe J. C. MARKS\nLIQUOR COMPANY\nWHOLESALE DEALERS\n439 WEST MAIN STREET, LOUISVILLE, KY.\nThe Recognized Whisky Market of the World.\nAll goods sent express charges prepaid, in nice, plain,\nI neat boxes, direct to your home. We do not send out any\ngoods that have not been .critically inspected by our\nsuperintendent.\nEXPRESS CHARGES PREPAID\n$8.00 for Four Full Quarts, very old Reserve Stock, Rye or Bourboa.\nr $7.00 for Four Full Quurts, Belgravia, Rye or Bourbon.\nj| $0.00 for Four Full Quarts, Exclusive Club, Rye or Bourbon.\nL $r>.00 for Four Full Quarts, Kcwnnce Pure Whisky, Rye or Bonrbon.\n$4.00 for Four Full Quarts, Royal Bond Rye (blended), French Grape\n|j Brandy, (Cognac), Peach Brandy and Rock Candy, for coughs and\ncolds.\nJ $3.20 for Four Full Quarts, Old Private Stock Rye, Old Plantation Corn,\nRanger Gin, Maryland Peach Brandy, Virginia Apple Brandy. j\n$4.00 for Four Full Quarts, Royal Bond, Bottled In Bond With Govern\nment Stamp on Top, Goods made In 1001.\n$4.00 for Four Full Quarts, Grape Brandy.\n$4.00 for Fonr Full Quarts Imported Pemartln Sherry Wine.\n$3.70 for Four Full Quarts, Imported Artaud Port Wine.\nj| $1.00 for Four Full Quarts California Wine, California Port, Sherry,\nAngelica, Sweet Catawba, Scuppcrnong.\nWe also carry a full line of Domestic and Imported f\nChampagnes.\nWrite for prices on any goods you want not quoted in\nj this advertisement.\nTHE J. C. MARKS LIQUOR CO.\n-WHOLESALE DEALERS-\n1 439 West Main Street, Louisville, Ky. i\n1 ESTABLISHED 1887\nI Send your personal check, Postal money order or\n1 Express money order. You can make same payable to J.\nI C. Marks if you desire.\nI We will *ort the Rood* up tor you any way you desire. We\nI do not shlp^ess than four quart, express prepaid. Write for\n1 wholesale price list; It\u2019a free.\nM\nGREAT OPPORTUNITY\nFOR DEMOCRATIC PARTY\nThe following address on \u201cDemocracy's\nOpportunity\u2019* was delivered at the recent\nJeffersoh banquet In New York city by\nPresident Woodrow Wilson of Princeton\nuniversity:\n\u201cWe heaf a great deal of candidacies\nand programmes, hut very little of prin\nciples. Parties seem almost to have gone\nto pioces and to have become indis\ntinguishable, except in so far as men by\nhabit call themselves by this party name\nor by.that. Both parties have with like\neagerness turned to the regulation of the\nbusiness of the country, the restraint and\nregulation of the great business corpora\ntions, and vie with each other in the rad\nical measures which they propose; but the\nmeasures of the one might be the meas\nures of the other. They are virtually in\ndistinguishable In principle, which, if car\nried far enough in Its application, would\nInevitably change the whole character of\nour government. It is time we stopped,\nfor a little while, speaking of candi\ndacies and undertook to test measures by\nprinciples.\nGreat Corporations.\n\u201cThe greater part of the business of the\ncountry has come into the hands of great\ncorporations and trusts, and its new as\npects unquestionably require adjustments\nand reformulations of the law. which the\ncourts have not had the power or the\ncourage to make, and which must there\nfore be made by legislation. The more\nscale of business operations, moreover,\nhas vastly Increased. Comparatively\nsmall groups of men In control of great\ncorporations wield a power and control\nover the wealth and the business opera\ntions of the country which makes them\nseem rivals of the government itself. Law\nmust be strengthened and adapted to keep\nthem in curb and to make them sub\nservient to the general welfare. No one\nnow advocates the old latssez falre; no\none questions the necessity for a Arm and\ncomprehensive regulation of business op\nerations in the interest of fair dealing,\nof a responsible exercise of power. W's\nare all advocates of a firm and effective\nregulation, hut those of us who are dem\nocrats challenge the prevailing principles\nof regulation, the principles which the re\npublican party has introduced and car\nried to such radical lengths, and which\nsome democrats confused by the clamour\nof the hour, have too thoughtlessly and\nhastily espoused.\nExecutive Regulations.\n\"We have in fact ^.turned from legal\nregulation to executive regulation. We\nhave turned from law to personal power.\nIt is that choice which as democrats we\nchallenge and challenge with confidence,\nas opposed to every ancient principle of\nliberty and of just government. Have\nwe given up law? Must we fall back on\ndiscretionary executive power? The gov\nernment of the United States was estab\nlished to get rid of arbitrary, that Is,\ndiscretionary executive power. If we re\nturn to it, we abandon the very prin\nciples of our foundation, give up the\nEnglish and American experiment and\nturn back to discredited models of gov\nernment.\n\u201cA mere casual examination of recent\nlegislation will show that these state\nments are not based upon fa-'.cy or upon\nexaggeration, but upon the necessary\ncharacter of the things we have been\ntrying to do. Law which cannot define\nand discriminate the transactions which\nIt Is the purpose of the legislature to\nforbid is not ready to become law at all,\nand yet it Is Just that that our recent\nstatutes enacted by way of regulating\nsome of the most Important enterprises\nof the country have failed to do. They\nhave run In vague terms, lumping things\npermissible with things impermissible, in\nterfering with business without analyzing\nIt or carefully discriminating Its good\nand bad features. And the when the re\nsults were unsatisfactory they have\nsought to lodge the power to discriminate,\nto permit and forbid, in the hands of\ncommissions with very extensive discre\ntionary powers, administrative In char\nacter, not Judicial; for no process is Ju\ndicial which does not rest upon deflniUan,\nupon detailed and explicit provisions of\nknown law. The Sherman act was as\nclumsy as it has been ineffectual, and\nthe remedy for it has been to lodge the\npower to discriminate between what It\nshould have forbidden and what it should\nhave permitted in the hands of bodies or\ncommissioners appointed by the Presi\ndent.\nTrusts Forbidden.\n\u201cThe latest proposals are typical of all\nthe rest. All combinations or agreements\nin restraint of trade had been forbidden\nby statute. But some agreements in re\nstraint of trade, some sorts of pooling of\nrates by the railroads for Instance, do\nnot In fact operate to the detriment of\nthe public or of trade itself, but are ben\neficial rather and to be desired in the In\nterest alike of efficiency and economy.\nThe lawmakers, upon that discovery, are\nnot Invited by the reformers to attempt\ndefinitions of law which will discriminate\nbetween those agreements in restraint of\ntrade which are innocent of monopolistic\nintent or effect and desirable In the in\nterest of the community itself, from those\nwhich the vague original law was in\ntended to prevent. They are urged, on\nthe contrary, to put the whole matter In\nthe hands of an executive officer. It is\nproposed to Invite all corporations which\nwish to keep within the limits of the\nlaw to register with him and submit all\ntlielr contracts and arrangements to him\nfor his sanction or disapproval, to let\nhim make law by executive order.\nUnderlying Principle.\n\"The principle underlying the laws\nwhich have here and there set up\npowerful public service commissions is\nthe same. These commissions are au\nthorized not to administer precise\nrules of law made clear in the defini\ntion of statutes, but to order this, that,\nor the other alteration, addition or ad\njustment in the actual administration\nof the business of the corporations\nwhich they are set to supervise. It is\ntrue that *hese corporations are In a\nsense public servants; street railway\ncompanies, gas lighting companies and\nthe like. They use the public high\nways and enjoy public franchises of\none kind or another and are engaged\nIn kinds of business which can hardly\nbe called private in character, but\nthey are owned by private capital and\noperated for private profit. And yet\ntheir business is regulated, even In Its\nchief administrative details, by public\nofficers whose practical Judgment is\nthe standard of regulation, who are\nadministering not rules of law but\ntheir own discretionary opinions. The\nlaw attempts no definitions in respect\nof these undertakings. It puts them In\nthe bands of public officers, and yet\nundertakes no responsibility for their\nsuccess or bankruptcy.\nPersonal Government.\n\u201cIf this is necessary, government by\nlaw has broken down, and personal i\ngovernment has been substituted.\nWhen those measures are understood,\nthe people of this country will turn\nfrom them and substitute law once\nmore for personal power.\n\u201cTo all thoughtful persons, scrupu\nlous of the ancient principles of our\nlaw. it Is evident where this demoral\nization crept In. It is plain why the\nfederal government has become the\npatron of the people Instead of the\narbiter of just and definite law'. Our\nlater tariff legislation has not been\nbased upon the general welfare, but\nupon the patronage of special Interests\nalready strong, already very influential\nin politics.\nDemocracy\u2019s Opportunity.\n\u201cThe opportunity, of the democratic\nparty is the same all along the line;\nto return to government by law; to\nInsist, upon a tariff reconsidered In all\nits definitions, adjusted to the actual\nconditions of trade and manufacture,\nviewed, not interest by interest, but\nupon the broad basis of the country's\nneeds and economies; to insist upon\na currency, not based upon the sale of\nthis, that or the other body or class\nof securities, but upon the actual as\nsets and soundness of the banks of\nIssue, redundancy checked by taxation,\nhazard offset by inspection for the en\nforcement of definite and uniform\nrules; to insist upon laws, whether of\ncombination or of contract, of offen\nsive or of defensive action, which shall\nbe the same for the capitalist and for\nthe laborer; to insist upon the precise\nfixing of responsibility on individuals;\nto insist, in brief, everywhere upon\ndefinitions, uniform, exact, enforceable.\n\u201cOur lawmakers have made too lit\ntle analysis of the things they wished\nto correct. Our law has not carefully\nenough discriminated real from nomi\nnal control, the masters from the ser\nvants. Our battle cry must be, \u201cBack\nto the region of law.\u201d The discrtlon\nof executive officers, whether you call\nthem commissioners or not, is a mere\nquicksand upon which no nation can\nstand.\u201d\nLETTERS TO THE EDITOR\nThe Red Mountain Tunnel,\nTo the Editor of The Agj-Herald:\nIt is with a great deal of Interest that\nI note from your paper the proposed tun\nnel through Red Mountain. Not only be\ncause having spent most of my life in\nand near Birmingham, though I am mak\ning this county nay home now, I still\nhave a broad, deep and lasting interest\nin the prosperity of your city and the\nsuccess of her citizens, but some 30-odd\nyears ago my father, Hon. W. T. Fulton,\nknown by many of the older citizens,\nlived on his farm Just beyond the south\nern extremity of the ravine spoken of in\nthe proposed site of the tunnel. This\nroute over the mountain was then a mere\ntrail or path, and I can remember, while\nriding behind my father hotseback, over\nthis trail of hearing him remark that\n\"some day in the future this mountain\nwill be tunneled at this point and people\nwill live in the valley and have their\nbusiness in the city.\" The benefit accru\ning from such Improvements, both to\nthe citizens in Shades valley and those\nin the city, is hard to calculate; to say\nthe least, it will be far more than the\ncost of the construction. My recollection\nis that the soil Is different, the water\ngenerally soft and the air the purest, in\nmy opinion this proposed tunnel is only\nthe first of several which, as my father\nprophesied, will be constructed \"some\ntime in the future.\u201d Yours truly,\nW. B. FULTON.\nDadeville, Ala., April 15, 1908.\nSuggests New Road.\nTo the Editor of The Age-Herald:\nVery much has been said through your\npaper about tunneling Red Mountain and\na number of citizens and taxpayers have\ntaken some thought about the matter and\nhave put themselves to some trouble In\nlooking into this matter to some extent.\nWe observe that a tunnel is unnecessary.\nWhat we suggest Is to continue the pres\nent Twentieth street car line from Fif\nteenth avenue, south, to a point about\nthe distance of two squares up Twenty\nfirst street. There the street or road\nturns almost due west. Now follow it\nabout six or eight feet, then turn south,\ngoing through the mountain by a cut,\nopening across to the railroad track that\nis now there. Then filling a valley on\nthe other side of the railroad with this\nearth taken out of this cut in the moun\ntain. There you have an opening all suf\nficient by making this road about 15 feet\nwider or some parts of it. A cost of about\n$15,000 will do all this work, while a tun\nnel would cost $100,000.\nJAMES A. ALLEN.\nBirmingham, April 15, 1908.\nPolitics Before Baseball.\nMemphis, April 15.\u2014Because of the In\ntense interest manifested in a local elec\ntion held today, the opening game of the\nSouthern league season was postponed\nuntil tomorrow.\n_\n__\u2014__ M ....I I\nCONGO SITUATION\nAGAIN DISCUSSED\nBrussels, April 15.\u2014The discussion on\nthe question of the annexation of the\nj Congo independent state began today in\nj the chamber of deputies, which was\ncrowded. Very little progress was made\nbesides clearing up preliminary matters.\nThe debate opened up by a'sharp at\ntack by the socialists, who accused the\ngovernment of wishing to rush the vote\non the annexation treaty and then shelve\nthe colonial bill. But a conclliary state\nment from Premier Schollaert smooted\nout the situation, whereupon M. Vander\nvelde, the socialist leader, declared that\nthe socialists would abstain from obstruc\ntion in any way. The Premier then\nsummed up the benefits which Belgium\nwould derive from the annexation of the\nCongo independent state, then the min\nister of foreign affairs followed tills with\nan explanation of the international situ\nation arising from the question which\nthe United States and Great Britain had\nsubmitted as to what steps were being\ntaken to carry out the terms of the Ber\nl lin treaty with regard to the rights of\ni the natives and the liberty of commerce.\nIt was decided that the debate on the\ntreaty shall continue without interruption\nuntil May 9. when the chamber will rise\nfor the elections.\nA special session of the chamber will\nbe called In June to deal with certain\nsupplementary points.\nPAUL ROY\u2019S CASE MAY SOUN BE\nTAKEN UP BY FRENCH COURTS\nParis, April 15.\u2014The department of\njustice has ordered M. Boucard, an\nexamining magistrate, to begin an in- j\nvestigation of the case of Paul Roy, j\nthe Frenchman who is accused by his i\nAmerican wife, known as \u201cGl&cia\nCalla,\u201d of killing her brother last Jan-\nuary at Newington, N. H. Should a\nformal prosecution in France be de\ncided upon, it is understood that the j\ndepositions of witnesses would be taken\nIn America and that it would not be j\nnecessary for them to come to France.\nIt was announced that M. Boucard,\nin the preliminary proceedings, proba*\nbly would summon before him Mrs.\nRoy, on account of the importance of\nher testimony.\nRoy came to Paris after the alleged\nmurder in New Hampshire and is now\nhere. Mrs. Roy is in the United States.\nFIRST SHIPMENT OF GOLD\nSINGE FINANCIAL PANIC\nNew York, April 15.\u2014The first en\ngagement of gold for shipment to Eu\nrope since the financial panic of Octo\nber last was announced today, the Na\ntional City bank taking $1,000,000 for\nParis.\nThe shipment is due to a rise in ex\nchange rates in New York and a <le- j\ncline in sterling in Paris. Germany is j\nreported to be bidding actively for\ngold In New York, and it was expected\nin Wall street today that gold would/1\ngo abroad in considerable quantities\nnext week. A report was current that i\nSecretary Cortelyou will call yn tTie\nbanks for government deposits if the\nmovement becomes too heavy.\nMAUNDY THURSDAY.\nImpressive Services In Catholic and\nEpiscopal Churches.\nTn the liturgical churches today is\nknown as Holy Thursday, or Maundy\nThursday. In most Catholic countries\nwashing the feet of the poor is prac\nticed as a ceremony and t,he hymn \u201cMan\naatum Novum\u201d is sung. The day derives\nits name from the \u201cnew commandment\u201d\nproclaimed in the gospel according to St.\nJohn xiii.\nAt St. Paul's church there will be a\nsolenyi high mass at 9 o\u2019clock and im\nmediately after the mass the blessed\nsacrament will be borne in solemn pro-\ncession from the high altar to the aJtar\nof repose. Tonight at 7:30 o\u2019clock the\nTenebrae will be sung and a sermon on\nthe holy eucharist will be preached by\nthe Rev. Father O\u2019Brien of Bessemer. j\nAt the Episcopal Church of the Ad- i\nvent Maundy Thursday will be celebrated\nwith a darkened communion service to\nnight at 8 o\u2019clock. Good Friday ser\nvices at the Advent will be held at 11 a.\nm. The rector, the Rev. Dr. W. E.\nEvans, will officiate.\nThe Rev. J. J. D. Hall will be the cele\nbrant at a darkened communion service\nat St. Mary\u2019s-on-the-Highlands tonight.\nThe complete order of services for to\nday and tomorrow (Good Friday) at St.\nMary\u2019s will be as follows:\nMaundy Thursday\u2014Litany, 7:30 a. m.;\nevening prayer, 5:30 p. m.; holy commun\nion, 8 p. m.\nGood Friday\u2014Litany, 7:30 a. m.; morn\ning prayer, 11 o\u2019clock.\nAda Illustrated with good cuts are\ntrade winners\u2014The Gawk makes rood\neats.\nI\nFULL ENJOYMENT\nIf no doubt exists in your mind as to the quality of f\ni an article; if you know it is good, believe its effect\nwill be beneficial\u2014then you really enjoy it OP\nPENHEIM\u2019S whisky begets just such confidence.\nPeople who know, and who buy the same goods\nfrom tfie same establishment yefar after year, order\nfrom us.\nPRICE LIST\nBiprrn Prepaid\u2014\u00abafp delivery guaranteed.\nOur Famous Brands\u2014Good (a r the Sick.\nRYE 14 Qts. 8 Qts. 12 Qt\u00ab.\nOlover.$3.40 6.65 9.75\nMistletoe. 4.00 7.75 11.00 j\nNo. 14. I.. 6.00 11.60 16.00\nOld Pharaoh.. 2.95\nCORN 4 Qts. 8 Qts. 12 Qta.\nPure Old Corn. ...$4.00 $7.75 $11.00\nOld gbaraoh.J 2.95\ng BOURBON 4 Qta. 